arch:property.oc:show_val: 2005 FUD: According to the excavator the unit deposit..."would appear to be dumping to fill up a small room in the southwest corner of a larger room" as indicated by the presence of burnt building material (mudbrick and plaster) and a large quantity of bone. This is a moderately sized unit with moderately weathered large pieces. There appears to be some breakage of bone in order to extract marrow but the conspicuous presence of vertebrae, ribs, and both ends of limb bones indicates that pulverization of bone for grease rendering was not undertaken. Species present include sheep, goat, cattle, a fair quantity of bird, and possibly small carnivore, while pig and horse are absent. Evidence of burning is rare as are signs of digestion. As for skeletal element distribution, the entire skeleton of sheep/goat is well represented, while cattle is somewhat rare. For sheep and goat the apparent ages range from newborn to adult. KCT noted both the high degree of integrity (high degree of elements that articulate) and the presence of vertebrae, which was unusual since these pieces were usually left off-site. There were (2) X-finds: One worked cattle shoulderblade, originally found near another second worked shoulderblade. There was some infantile human bone (9 rib fragments, 1 vertebral fragment and an almost complete clavicle), which were not recorded but sent to human bone lab, since they appear to have a skull that may be associated. Notes for priority feedback: ""Strange! Big unit with moderately weathered big pieces. Minimally processed (some complete bones, most fractured for marrow but not grease). For caprines all body parts represented; relatively little cattle. Range of ages, perinatal on, for caprines. 2 X-finds: one worked cattle scapula, found near another possibly worked scapula. Goat, sheep, cattle; no pig or cervid, a couple of pieces of fox. High integrity; a number of articulations. Lots of bird! Very little burning, very little digestion. Looks like lots of pieces, relatively little processed, in weird context. Quite atypical. Bones appear to have gone in very directly. Lots of vertebrae: the parts that usually seem to get left off site." Season 2006: Completing recording of 11644-- recording was not completed in 2005. 2006 recording by AD and KCT. New FUD composed at this time. Many specimens are quite large, in the vicinity of 8-10 cm long. Weathering moderate. Cut marks apparent clearly on one pelvis, in the classic location above the acetabulum; two other shaft fragments and a mandible heel may also have CM. Notable finds include a more or less complete cattle scapula burnisher (X4), another possible one (X5), a polished MT(distal end and shaft, squared off) (X7). X10 is actually a neonate- infantile spinal column segment from a sheep-sized animal. The vertebral centra are not fused to the arches, and the centra are roughly 2/3 cm wide. The vertebrae are not human. The vertebrae include 6 lumbars and 8 thoracics. Three tiny rib heads are also included. There is baby human present as well: a tibia, a fibula, some pelvis, and at least one other unidentified long bone. Roddy remembers these bones as scattered, not attributable to a defined baby burial, though there may be part of a disturbed burial in the fill. Several pieces of bird, including a remarkably complete carpometacarpus of a medium-large bird (about 2/3 stork-size). The bird remains are primarily (potentially, all, depending on further analysis) forelimb bones, including also a large ulnar carpal and some phalanx fragments. 4mm scrap 100% sorted, recorded. Last F number = 480.
